Snape Maltings: a community in tune with its surroundings
The movie Quartet told the story of musicians who retired with like-minded folk. Harry de Quetteville finds a real-life version
at Snape Maltings in Suffolk.
Rich heritage: not only are the views from Snape Maltings inspiring, but the development is full of character with the comforts of modern living By Harry de Quetteville
8:00AM GMT 11 Feb 2013
Comments
Small, tightly knit communities have always been catnip to screenwriters. With everyone living on top of each other, it’s hard not to suspect, and sneakily hope, that love and intrigue lie just beneath the surface. If you are visiting, you just have to cross your fingers and hope that things are more Downton Abbey than EastEnders – or worse, Midsomer Murders. Snape Maltings, in Suffolk, inland from Aldeburgh, is just such a vibrant, energetic community in the making. Here, 65 houses and flats are being wrested from lovely, but crumbling, industrial buildings on a seven-acre site that is also home to the renowned Aldeburgh Festival. Thirty have already been completed, with around half of them occupied by people who have opted to live there full-time. Although the development has not been specifically conceived with retirees in mind, many of the buyers are people who have stopped working and are drawn to this lovely corner of Suffolk. For them, music is one of the main attractions. Indeed, watching the residents of Snape Maltings drift about serenely one wintry morning the thought strikes me: this is not Midsomer (thank God) or Albert Square. I have accidentally stumbled on a real-life version of the Dustin Hoffman-directed movie Quartet. That film, you may remember, stars Tom Courtenay, Pauline Collins, and Billy Connolly as opera singers who in their dotage have retired to a swish retreat, Beecham House. Old passions and tempests are rekindled as Maggie Smith arrives on the scene and the four principals prepare for a concert to celebrate Verdi’s birthday. Related Articles
Top 20 celebrity retirement hot spots
15 Nov 2012
Quartet
01 Jan 2013
Dustin Hoffman directs Quartet: Set report
01 Jan 2013
'Quartet’ shows the way to bring harmony to old age
07 Jan 2013
Making music key to happy retirement, research says
24 Nov 2011
So often excluded from Hollywood’s depiction of vivacious living, these retirees are shown in full swing, enjoying life to the full. And what’s going on at Snape Maltings proves that such an existence for the over-65s – the chance to retire among like-minded people – needn’t be merely a cinematic fantasy. Around these impressive buildings, it isn’t hard to imagine gossipy intrigue among friends who share the same passions. Many of the first 20 flats that were built, for example, look out on to a charming courtyard. Perfect for a quiet natter with – or preferably about – the neighbours. “We started planning in 2004 and began to finish the first phase in 2007 just as the downturn hit,” explains John Gooderham, whose family have owned the site since 1965. “Even so, it has been a real success. All the first 20 flats sold. Alesha and John Gooderham have established a retreat to offer buyers the chance to live with people who share their interests “Half the buyers have been looking for a second home. The rest are here to stay, retiring to live here full-time. They’ve been able to move into brand-new homes on an old site. So they don’t have to worry about repairs but they can enjoy the heritage.”
Phase two was completed last year. It comprises 10 four-bedroom homes that, unlike the flats, look out on the reeds and marshland of the Alde estuary towards the picturesque St Botolph’s Church at Iken. It’s a stunning view, though not, I have to say, totally unimpeded (by lights and parking). “The whole project should be finished in 2018,” says John. “It really goes to show what private enterprise can do – taking on a big project and making it work in a sympathetic way. Planners know that we’re not here to make a fast buck. They understand that the Gooderham family has been here for years and is here to stay.” The intervention is much needed. Phase three, with 35 flats, will be crafted from the shell of one of the biggest buildings yet to be salvaged. Its condition is evidence of what would have happened to this place if it had been left to drift. Old winches and girders are rusting and imperilled. The hulks of two old cars sit rotting. It’s atmospheric. But not exactly uplifting. And yet, I’m humming. The reason is blowing in the wind. As in Quartet, music is everywhere at Snape Maltings. Just opposite the ruin is a large rehearsal complex for the festival eked from a series of once equally derelict buildings. Around the corner, the main concert hall and opera house sits under a roof sporting distinctive square malthouse vents. And although the annual festival, which this year features such renowned artists as Judith Weir and the Hallé Orchestra, is not staged until June, there’s a busy year-round programme of events. Musicians carrying violins and tubas bustle about, semibreves and quavers linger in the air. When all 65 properties are completed, there are likely to be almost 100 people living here full-time, with double that at busy times. The real-life Beecham House, it seems, has arrived. Except that the composer in question is not Verdi but the festival’s founder Benjamin Britten, who lived in nearby Aldeburgh for 30 years and whose centenary is celebrated this year. The film 'Quartet' is about opera singers who have retired to a swish retreat, Beecham House The other principal difference is that where Beecham (in reality Hedsor House, in Bucks) is a glorious Georgian mansion, Snape Maltings is an industrial relic. No matter. For there is something so evocative about Victorian industrial architecture. It’s the way that individual buildings were plugged into the nation’s infrastructure network to become part of something seamless, something bigger than themselves. The grand planners of that era seem in retrospect like boys dreaming of the layout of their model railway sets – dreamers plotting the carefully synchronised moves of each signal and locomotive. Indeed, the traces of what used to be the railway at Snape are still clear. The branch line opened in 1859, with a daily goods service that hauled the malt to London’s breweries. The locomotive terminated on the site, and rails ran throughout the complex. They went between the malt houses and stores, and down to the quay, where the Alde still broadens in anticipation of the sea just five miles away. What had previously been a remote corner of the countryside, best-suited to smuggling, was suddenly accessible, prosperous even. But the dream of those boys with their train sets faded as it did in so many other places. Gradually the pace and production at these marvellous red-brick buildings slowed. Grand open spaces which had once respired easily with the ambition of the times fell silent and died. And began, in many cases, to crumble. Many such spaces around the country, particularly in city centres, have since been refurbished by upmarket developers. But they have always seemed a touch soulless to me, the stripping away of their grand Victorian purpose removing an essential part of their identity. There is a hopeful sense, however, that things might be different at Snape. For there is a big idea here, one that yokes nature with music and a very definite style of life to bring bustle once again to a corner of the world that was in danger of simply rotting away. This is a project that rings with the best of Victorian-era enlightened entrepreneurialism. The community identity is reinforced by shops which sell everything from aprons to children’s toys to furniture (all in the best possible taste, of course). The food hall is being enlarged and will open soon. “We’ve kept on expanding what’s on offer here on site,” John says. “People can get a lot of what they need on foot.” Shopping and music are not the only activities on the menu. On the day I visited, the on-site Café 1885 was running a course on how to cook game. Elsewhere footpaths lead directly away from the site into a nature reserve. As I strolled towards Iken on a crisp, bright morning, a kingfisher darted through the reeds in front of me, just one of the species that makes this a birdwatchers’ paradise. One resident couple do better than walk – having bought their own boat they can putter out into the estuary, getting closer than ever to the wildlife. Others, no doubt, will prefer the social delights of living cheek-by-jowl with their fellows. For although it must be eminently possible to live a happy life in isolation, surely the point is to get stuck in. Maggie Smith would. After all, as Jane Austen so famously observed in her novel Pride and Prejudice: “For what do we live, but to make sport for our neighbours?” Three-bedroom town house at Snape Maltings starts from £550,000 to £650,000. They are available through Savills (01603 229 229)
