Who is at fault: Eden Hazard or Swansea ballboy?
Those who seek to defend Eden Hazard need their eyesight, sanity and moral compass checking. Hazard was a fool who kicked a ballboy, who set fire to the Football Association’s Respect document and dragged Chelsea into another fine mess.
Seeing red: Eden Hazard looked bemused when referee Chris Foy waved the red card but he had to go Photo: GETTY IMAGES	By Henry Winter, Football Correspondent
11:59PM GMT 24 Jan 2013
Follow Comments
You cannot kick ballboys, whatever the desire to flick a ball loose, whatever the provocation of a self-admiring teenager. Ballboys should be seen and not hurt. Such has been the perfect snowstorm of tribalism, naivety and sanctimony following events 10 minutes from time at the Liberty Stadium on Wednesday that the simple truth is in danger of being clouded. Hazard kicked Charlie Morgan, a ballboy mature in years if immature in behaviour. Hazard risked a criminal charge. And just imagine the headlines of horror and outpouring of outrage on the airwaves and social media had Morgan kicked Hazard. It was disappointing to hear usually sanguine voices like Pat Nevin eviscerating Morgan. Michael Owen, another traditionally rational observer, was also critical. So was Jason Cundy. Hazard himself looked bemused when Chris Foy waved the red card: the impertinence, the indignity, the injustice. What nonsense. Hazard had to go and faces an extension to the three-match ban if the FA’s charred Respect edict is to have any credibility. His argument that he was kicking the ball is irrelevant; he made contact with Morgan. Related Articles
Alan Smith: blame it on the ballboy
24 Jan 2013
Who is ballboy Charlie Morgan?
24 Jan 2013
FA Cup has huge worth for Benitez
24 Jan 2013
Swansea escape FA action
24 Jan 2013
Chelsea's Hazard escapes police charges
24 Jan 2013
Belgian FA: We are not proud of Hazard
24 Jan 2013
Hazard shamed his club and his sport. He is a professional sportsman paid handsomely to be disciplined. He is a role model who exploits his appeal to impressionable youth financially through a boot deal with Nike. He is bright enough to know that tangling with ballboys is wrong. Chelsea, to their eventual credit, admitted Hazard erred and made him issue a partial mea culpa. Frank Lampard’s compassion towards Morgan reflected that the midfielder, a true leader, realised that this was another PR disaster for a club who have endured a few. Lampard’s fine behaviour was another reason why Chelsea are mad not to keep this soulful, responsible ambassador. Still, Chelsea will be represented by Hazard, the scourge of ballboys who will now be targeted by opposition fans. Where Hazard supporters like Nevin, Owen, Cundy and company suffer most from myopia is in not seeing the harm to the sport they love. To the footballing agnostic (about half the country if broadcasters are to be believed), Hazard’s kick was another sign of the arrogance of the modern millionaire footballer. The alienation from the modern game continues. Hazard deserves all the opprobrium from right-minded onlookers and whatever additional spell on the naughty step decreed by the FA beaks. It is also to be hoped that Martin Morgan, a director of the club, has a word with his time-wasting, limelight-seeking son whose self-aggrandising tendencies are seen in his twitter account handle boasting a rather presumptuous “TM” trademark logo. If Morgan wanted fame, he has certainly got it. Infamy in many eyes. He embarrassed his father and the club. Pity. The Liberty is one of the friendliest grounds to visit: Swansea City’s staff are chatty and helpful while fans stroll up before kick-off to engage in a natter about the game. The players and the manager, Michael Laudrup, represent the club well. The full-back Àngel Rangel modestly admitted to passing round food for the homeless. Morgan’s unwillingness to release the ball to Hazard contrasted with the intrinsically classy nature of Swansea City Football Club. Morgan also distracted from one of the most special nights in Swansea’s history. People should have been talking about defender Ashley Williams. Afterwards, Laudrup was besieged with questions about ballboys and belligerent Belgians. But it was the briefing with Rafael Benítez that was really the all-ticket affair. Benítez, sensibly, agreed that Hazard was culpable, then added that Morgan was to blame and so was society. Press conferences with Benítez usually meander through such territory as Lampard’s future, Fernando Torres’s body language, and the interim first-team manager’s relationship with Chelsea’s fans and the club’s owner Roman Abramovich. Here it hurtled into Desmond Morris country. At one point, as Benítez argued that Morgan was effectively a product of a “Big Brother culture”, discreet inquiries were made over whether the Spaniard was referring to George Orwell or Jade Goody. Benítez had a legitimate point, though, about youngsters’ obsession with becoming celebrities. Note to Morgan. Read up on Icarus. In truth, Benítez should really raise a quiet glass of Rioja to Morgan and Hazard. The spotlight on the ballboy tore the focus away from Chelsea’s largely limp display and Benítez’s own guilt in not changing the system and personnel earlier. Benítez’s meek surrender let down those many Chelsea fans who slalomed and skidded west and east along the snow-strewn M4. Hazard let them down even more. You do not kick ballboys. Chelsea
